values:
It's Friday once again (&quot;Friday Friday gotta get down on Friday&quot; - and now I'll have that in my head for the rest of the day) and I'm in work and London is having grey and miserable weather.&nbsp; 

Non -UK residents may wonder when London is not grey and miserable as popular culture suggests we have never really been blessed with sunshine.&nbsp; Admittedly we are a country who apparently pissed off whichever of the pantheon it is who looks after weather. Not as bad as some other countries one might say - extreme weather is a rarity here - but perhaps we did something nationally on about the same level of irritation as door to door salesmen or annoying advertising jingles on the TV, which results in our Summer being broken up with patches of cold miserable grey weather better suited to the opposite side of the year.

There's an old joke about Northern European Summers:

&quot;Do you remember last Summer?&quot;

&quot;Yes, it was a Tuesday wasn't it&quot; or &quot;That last weekend in May&quot; or the old favourite &quot;No - there was a summer?&quot;

And it's no less true for repetition.&nbsp; 

There has, to my recollection, been one weekend of Summer so far this year.&nbsp; It was early, as Summer's are wont to be, around that first weekend in May, and I spent it with friends - sitting out in Regent's Park on the Saturday and barbequeing on the Sunday (or it might have been the bank holiday Monday, I forget).&nbsp; But I spent it, as I do each year, thinking &quot;Wow Summer's great - hope it like this the whole time,&quot; and it never is.

Never stops me thinking it though.&nbsp; I guess I never learn.
